04747nam a22005535i 9780226817439DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212006ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226817439  a(DE-B1597)575526  a(OCoLC)1248759420  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQA76 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a303.48/33  aAN 92650qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/6750:1 aTurner, Fred, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Counterculture to Cyberculture :bStewart Brand, the Whole Earth Network, and the Rise of Digital Utopianism /cFred Turner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (354 p.) :b16 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Shifting Politics of the Computational Metaphor -- t2. Stewart Brand Meets the Cybernetic Counterculture -- t3. The Whole Earth Catalog as Information Technology -- t4. Taking the Whole Earth Digital -- t5. Virtuality and Community on the WELL -- t6. Networking the New Economy -- t7. Wired -- t8. The Triumph of the Network Mode -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early 1960s, computers haunted the American popular imagination. Bleak tools of the cold war, they embodied the rigid organization and mechanical conformity that made the military-industrial complex possible. But by the 1990s—and the dawn of the Internet—computers started to represent a very different kind of world: a collaborative and digital utopia modeled on the communal ideals of the hippies who so vehemently rebelled against the cold war establishment in the first place. From Counterculture to Cyberculture is the first book to explore this extraordinary and ironic transformation. Fred Turner here traces the previously untold story of a highly influential group of San Francisco Bay–area entrepreneurs: Stewart Brand and the Whole Earth network. Between 1968 and 1998, via such familiar venues as the National Book Award–winning Whole Earth Catalog, the computer conferencing system known as WELL, and, ultimately, the launch of the wildly successful Wired magazine, Brand and his colleagues brokered a long-running collaboration between San Francisco flower power and the emerging technological hub of Silicon Valley. Thanks to their vision, counterculturalists and technologists alike joined together to reimagine computers as tools for personal liberation, the building of virtual and decidedly alternative communities, and the exploration of bold new social frontiers. Shedding new light on how our networked culture came to be, this fascinating book reminds us that the distance between the Grateful Dead and Google, between Ken Kesey and the computer itself, is not as great as we might think.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aComputer networksxSocial aspects. 0aComputers and civilization. 0aCounterculturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aInformation technologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSubculturezCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryy20th century. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszCalifornia, Northern. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acounterculture, cyberculture, whole earth network, digital age, internet, online, stewart brand, communication, popular imagination, computers, transformation, san francisco bay, united states of america, american culture, usa, well, wired magazine, silicon valley, technology, information technologies, 20th century, subculture, history, historical.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978022681